{{Infobox language |name=Bartangi |states=[[Gorno-Badakhshan Autonomous Province]] |ethnicity=3,000 [[Bartang people|Bartang]] (1990)<ref>{{e19|sgh|Shughni}}</ref> |speakers=? |date= |ref= |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] |fam3=[[Iranian languages|Iranian]] |fam4=[[Eastern Iranian languages|Eastern]] |fam5=[[Shugni–Yazgulami]] |fam6=Shughnani |script=None |iso3=none |iso3comment=(included in {{ethnolink|sgh}}) |glotto=bart1238 |glottorefname=Bartangi }}
The '''Bartangi language''' is a [[Pamir languages|Pamir language]] spoken along the [[Bartang River]] from [[Yemtz]] to [[Nikbist]], in [[Gorno-Badakhshan Autonomous Region]]. It is typically classified as a dialect of [[Shughni language|Shughni]], but is quite distinct. Within Bartangi, there are two (sub)dialects, Basid and Sipandzh, which are named after the villages in which they are spoken.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kolga|first1=Margus|title=The Red Book of the Peoples of the Russian Empire|date=2001|publisher=Tallinn|url=http://www.eki.ee/books/redbook/bartangs.shtml}}</ref> It is not written.
As of 1990, there are between 2,500{{cn|date=May 2015}} and 3,000 speakers of Bartangi. While the population continues to grow, civil war and Russian efforts to assimilate the Bartangi or move them to cities have caused the language to dwindle. In addition, the popularity of [[Tajik language|Tajik]] and [[Russian language|Russian]] as the languages of education and modernization have contributed to the decline of Bartangi.
Bartangi is most similar to [[Rushani dialect|Rushani]] and [[Orosori dialect|Orosori]], two neighboring Sughni dialects. Features that distinguish them include the form of the second person{{fix|text=inflection? pronoun?}}, a ''tu'' tense in Bartangi,{{what|date=May 2015}} and the Bartangi plural suffix ''-en''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bartangi|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/bartangi-a-member-of-the-sugni-q}}</ref>
==Discovery and decline== The language was unknown to Europe until the early twentieth century, when French linguist Robert Gauthiot published his findings on the area in his 1916 essay ''Notes sur le yazgoulami, dialecte iranien des confins du Pamir.''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kolga|first1=Margus|title=The Red Book of the Peoples of the Russian Empire|url=http://www.eki.ee/books/redbook/bartangs.shtml}}</ref> After the discovery of the Bartangi people, there was an increase in interest in the Shughni provinces, but due to the difficult landscape, very few explorers visited the area, and publications on the language dropped off, though in 1924 a Bartangi lullaby was printed.
The next major European involvement in the area was by the Russians, who over the course of the nineteenth century had conquered parts of [[Tajikistan]] until its formal declaration as the [[Tajik Soviet Socialist Republic]] in 1929. Despite Tajikistan declaring independence in 1991, permanent Russian influence in language, culture, and politics have led to the loss of several Pamir languages. Tajik, an Iranian language which is the national language of Tajikistan, serves as a common language through all Tajik provinces. In addition, with a 96% literacy rate throughout the province, even the isolated region of Bartang is well-versed in the national languages of Tajik, Uzbek, and Russian.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jernudd|first1=Bjorn|title=The Language Situation in Tadzhik SSR|journal=Anthropological Linguistics|date=1965|volume=7|issue=3|pages=76–83}}</ref> Russian is currently the language of education and the intelligentsia in Tajikistan, and the influence of these larger languages are required for communication between speakers of the various Pamir languages.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jernudd|first1=Bjorn|title=The Language Situation in Tadzhik SSR|journal=Anthropological Linguistics|date=1965|volume=7|issue=3|pages=76–83}}</ref>
War has also contributed to substantial decline of the Shughni languages, and Bartangi is no exception. World War II, conflicts between Shughni villages, and the civil war which ravished the province from 1992 to 1997, all contributed to the diminishing status of the language. In addition to wiping out portions of the population, the war forced many of the Pamir inhabitants out of their native lands and into cities, where their languages are of little use. The 1950s also saw massive resettlement of Bartang people, though the population has been increasing since 1959.
