In [[computer slang]], '''J. Random Hacker''' is an arbitrary [[programmer]] ([[Hacker (programmer subculture)|hacker]]).
{{quote|A mythical figure like the [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier|Unknown Soldier]]; the archetypal hacker [[nerd]]. This term is one of the oldest in the [[Hacker (programmer subculture)|hacker's]] [[jargon]], apparently going back to [[MIT]] in the 1960s. may originally have been inspired by ‘[[J. Fred Muggs]]’, a show-biz [[chimpanzee]] whose name was a household word back in the early days of [[TMRC]], and was probably influenced by ‘[[J. Presper Eckert]]’ (one of the co-inventors of the [[electronic computer]])".|"A Portrait of J. Random Hacker"|the [[Jargon File]]<ref>[http://www.catb.org/jargon/html/appendixb.html Appendix B. A Portrait of J. Random Hacker], from the [[Jargon File]]</ref>}}
"J. Random Hacker" is a popular [[placeholder name]] in a number of books and articles in programming.<ref>''The Art of Unix Programming'' by [[Eric S. Raymond]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=CZae0PbOXJMC&pg=PA456&dq=%22J.+Random+Hacker%22#PPA457,M1 p. 457]</ref><ref>''Beginning Python'', by [[Peter Norton]] ''et al.'', p. 322</ref> J. Random Hacker even authored a book about ease of malicious hacking, ''Adventures of a Wi-Fi Pirate''.<ref>J. Random Hacker, ''Adventures of a Wi-Fi Pirate'' (2005) {{ISBN|1-930919-62-X}}</ref> Also, ''J. Random Hacker'' was a main developer of [[I2P]] software.
Over time, '''J. Random X''' has become a popular [[cliché]], a [[snowclone]], in computer lore, with more types of "[[random]]" (meaning "arbitrary") categories of people, such as "J. Random [[Newbie]]",<ref>''The Art of Unix Programming'' by Eric S. Raymond, Section "[http://www.faqs.org/docs/artu/ch16s01.html The tale of J. Random Newbie]"</ref> J. Random User,<ref>''TCP/IP Clearly Explained'', by Peter Loshin, [https://books.google.com/books?id=22mBxNqHTcsC&pg=PA116&dq=%22J.+random+user%22&lr= p. 116]</ref> or J. Random [[Luser]].
